{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"69e4f6ee-2e98-452a-9850-1ab5045478de","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n// or for theories:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\nAll four support a reason string. The key difference is xUnit, where `Skip` is a property on `[Fact]`/`[Theory]` rather than a separate attribute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9e5df3cd-8b4e-469e-908f-27ce29d8f739","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test skip attributes across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. I have a skill available called `dotnet-test-frameworks` that contains reference data for .NET test framework detection patterns, including skip annotations. Let me invoke it.\n\nWait, the skill description says \"DO NOT USE directly — loaded by test analysis skills\". But it also says it has skip annotations data. Let me check the available skills again.\n\nThe description says \"DO NOT USE directly — loaded by test analysis skills (test-anti-patterns, exp-test-smell-detection, exp-assertion-quality, exp-test-maintainability, exp-test-tagging) when they need framework-specific lookup tables.\"\n\n\nI can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to invoke the skill—it's a straightforward question about framework attributes.","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"0443:26AFE8:1813A20:1B5FA14:69E81E62"},"id":"a3e4a4de-531b-4b16-943d-5a4172d437db","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:42.802Z","parentId":"915aab2c-cdae-4934-a020-799319dfc5df"}
